 by canoe to make the drawings of the pictographs which illustrate every page of this fascinating and attractive book. He provides also a general analysis of the materials used by the Indians, of their subject-matter and the artistic rendering given to it, and his artist's journal records in detail the sites he visited, the paintings he found at each, the comparisons among them that came to mind, the references to rock paintings in early literature of the Northwest. Kenneth E. Kidd contributes a valuable essay on the anthropological background of the area, linking the rock paintings with early cave art in, for example, France and Spain, describing the life of the Indians in the Shield country, and commenting on what the pictographs reveal of their makers' attitudes to their external world and of their thinking. This is a book which will appeal to a wide audience: to those interested in primitive art forms and in Canadian art in general, to all students of the early history of North America, to travellers who in increasing numbers follow the canoe trails of the Shield lakes and rivers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIndians of North AmericazGreat Lakes Region (North America)xAntiquities. 0aRock paintingszGreat Lakes Region (North America). 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aFrost, Leslie M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKidd, Kenneth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144265374040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442653740423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442653740.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Pac